    "Prop Firm",
    "prop firm"
  ],
  "school": "Risk Management",
  "definition": "A proprietary trading firm providing funded trading accounts with a fixed drawdown limit. The trader's true risk capital is the drawdown amount, not the nominal account size, so position sizing must be calculated against the drawdown rather than the headline account value.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Account is offered as a 'funded' or evaluation account with a stated nominal size (e.g. $25K) but an associated maximum drawdown (e.g. $1,500) that defines actual loss tolerance.",
    "Position sizing is treated as a percentage of the drawdown limit rather than the nominal account size.",
    "Distinguish evaluation phase (higher risk per trade: 7–10% of drawdown) from funded phase (lower risk per trade for larger cushion)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Risk per trade must be calculated from the drawdown limit, not the nominal account size. On a $25K account with $1,500 drawdown, risking 1% of nominal ($250) is actually 17% of drawdown and blows the account in 6–7 losses. Instead, risk 7–10% of the drawdown during evaluation to allow 10–15 consecutive losses before failure. Once funded, lower the risk percentage to build a larger cushion. Same logic applies to both Futures and Forex prop firms.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Sizing trades as a percentage of the nominal account size instead of the drawdown limit, leading to an account blow-up within only 6–7 losing trades.",
    "Using the same risk percentage during the funded phase as during evaluation, instead of lowering risk after funding for a larger cushion."
  ],
